          <source>Key SRE principles and practices: The human side of SRE</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Key SRE principles and practices: The human side of SRE</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Key SRE principles and practices: The human side of SRE</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Check your knowledge</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Which of these things is <bpt id="p1">*</bpt>not<ept id="p1">*</ept> a characteristic of toil (in the SRE context)?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>The work is repetitive</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Toil is repetitive in nature.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>The work is tracked in a ticket system</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>How the work is tracked is not a characteristic of toil.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>While toil is often tracked this way, ticket systems could be used to track other, more productive kinds of work.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>The work provides no lasting value</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Work that is toil has no enduring value.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>The work is largely manual in nature and not automated</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="114" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Toil is almost always manual work that could be automated.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="115" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>What's an SRE's relationship to toil?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="116" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>SREs work to eliminate toil as their first priority.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="117" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Whenever possible, SREs work to eliminate toil, but sometimes other work has greater priority.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="118" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>SREs attempt to manage toil the best they can.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="119" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>SREs prefer to eliminate toil if possible.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="120" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Well-managed toil is still toil.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="121" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>SREs work to eliminate toil wherever and whenever it is appropriate</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="122" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>What is a suggested breakdown of work for an SRE?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="123" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>80% reactive ops work/20% project work</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="124" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>An SRE needs uninterrupted time to work on improving the reliability of a system, not just tending to its current needs.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="125" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>10% reactive ops work/90% project work</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="126" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>Sometimes we do not get a choice how much operational load a systems requires.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="127" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>While it may be the case that some systems have this low of an operational load, it is probably not a good expectation to have.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="128" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>50% reactive ops work/50% project work</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="129" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.intro-to-site-reliability-engineering.5-key-principles-2-human-side-of-sre">
          <source>This is the usual balance SREs strive for (50% is seen as an upper bound on operational load--smaller would be better).</source>
        </trans-unit></group></body></file></xliff>